description.long_derivative_description: D5 [215] R DESIGN Lux Nav 5dr AWD

comment.editorialComment: You might expect to see this sector showing some strength at this time of the year but the picture these days is quite different. Nowadays, almost every manufacturer now has an offering of some sort or other that fits the category of SUV but the reality is that these are more of a mainstream vehicle than some of the true 4x4’s that used to drive a very clear pattern of seasonality in this sector and the volumes reflect that. To put this in perspective, in 2012 there were just under 300,000 units registered in this sector. Last year that number had risen to just short of 620,000. This means that the majority of vehicles within this sector now behave more in line with the normal market and with the exception of a few of the more specialist vehicles, we would expect to see an overall drop in values of around -1.5% for November.

This sector has seen more growth over the last few years than most and this is not only growth in registration volumes but also in the sheer number of models that are now available. This has changed the way that most of this sector behaves in terms of seasonality. Historically, you would always expect to see values strengthening at this time of the year but with the increasing numbers of crossover vehicles rather than true 4x4’s this sector has become more mainstream and we would expect to see values across all but the more specialist vehicles reduce in line with the overall market during December.

Most people would expect to see values in this sector only go one way during January and that of course is up. That perception has been driven in the past by a very strong seasonality effect ass demand for these types of vehicles goes up during the winter months. However, these days because this sector is so big and so diverse, that seasonality doesn’t always show. What will happen though, is that there will be a big push to generate extra business during January and vehicles from this sector are likely to play a larger part in that. That doesn’t necessarily mean that values will drop because the balance of supply and demand during January will keep buyers on their toes and this will most likely lead to a rise in values as we go through the month.
